@firedragon 1. Why would he not get a statement off her? The main relationship he had that was most like the one he was in with Amber, the one where there were plenty of reports at the time of it getting physical and where we had the incident where the police were called. Not to mention Amber had prior to the case mentioned a story about him pushing her down the stairs (it may have even been in the Suns article if I remember rightly). It's the statement that would have done the most to help him, not two women who are known to be more meek and as such most likely to just remove themselves from the situation when he is intoxicated.
2. The time excuse is a poor one. Cases aren't limited by a length of time. If they helped his case and it meant taking an extra few days it would have been worth it. And it wasn't just his ex's he didn't call, almost everyone he relied on statements from he didn't call. Statements alone are worth very little as an important part legal system is the ability to question those who give evidence. 
3. You seem to be getting mistaken for the difference between a crushing injury and a crushing cut. A bottle hitting a finger might cause a crushing injury but not a crushing cut it wouldn't, it would have to break and then that would be a slice. A crushing cut happens when you clamp down on either something that's already broken or which breaks under the pressure and the act of clamping causes it to cut
4. I'm not assuming being a hopeless addict equals a violent personality BUT in his case, there is evidence even from before Amber that thats where he goes. He has a history of smashing things up when intoxicated, he has a number of settled cases for an assault that happened when intoxicated etc. You have to remember that often the thing that stops people from being aggressive when sober isn't because they don't have that raw anger in them but it's the conditioning they have that allows them keep it in check. When intoxicated your conscious thinking is impaired, you are controlled more by subconscious and instincts. So an angry side can come out. He admits himself in texts to the likes of paul Bettany he gets aggressive and angry when intoxicated
5. Most bodyguards have de-escalation training so they usually wouldn't need to lay a hand on her. Even if they did they also have training on how to get physical to stop a threat in the correct way. Their job is to protect their client so the idea they would be wary of doing so for the threat of being accused of assault doesn't really fit
6. I didn't say any mental health issue does excuse her. I've said over and over again I feel they are both guilty, they both need to stop acting like little kids in the playground going 'she hit me first' 'no he hit me first'. They need to be adults and admit to whatever problems they have that makes them abusive and get the right help but they won't

@Simon Wakefield 

Re 1: Kate Moss. It may not have been confirmed but you're going to say it, without evidence, anyway.  Media reports or police reports?

Re 3: You're are correct, it was a crushing injury.  A full bottle slamming into a marble countertop with a finger between the two would cause a crushing injury, not slicing as bottle would be intact until it hit counter. Slicing could possibly only occur if a broken bottle was thrown.
